\paperw12240\paperh15840\margl1800\margr1800\margt1440\margb1440\deftab1195\f0\fs24\cf0
\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A Solitant priest hears the word \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91white\u8217\'92 and thinks of the pure white glow of Solraheen, a white so bright it bursts out of itself then scatters into rays of red, green, and blue. Hrkan folk hear \u8216\'91white\u8217\'92 and think of the plain and stainless robes of Hrkan Lordship. Outland pokes hear \u8216\'91white\u8217\'92 and think of sparkling salt pans and sun-bleached bone. As it is with white, so it is with words, they mean different things to different people. It is some wonder then, that Solraheen would choose to use a word to create the world. He dwelt in the void, spoke one word, the world emerged, and people haven\u8217\'92t stopped arguing about the meaning of it all ever since.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The problem is that words change meaning, acquire new meaning, or lose their meaning altogether. One might be led to believe that Solraheen chose to create with such a malleable thing as a word because He wanted to play with what He meant. But this is false, or so the Solitants claim. Words are fixed, or at least they were.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The word \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91art\u8217\'92, for example, originally had a clear meaning. Back when Solraheen walked the earth an artwork was nothing less than a divine message given physical form. Then evil came into the world, twisted the tongues of men, and now the heresy of art as a means of personal expression pollutes the minds of many.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 An old Solitant sermon titled \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91Art as Exegetical Instrument\u8217\'92 extracts the truth of the matter through interrogation:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 What is art?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Who is an artist?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Who isn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A painter, a sculptor, these are artists, yes, that\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s reasonable to say, but what about a tax collector? Is he an artist too if he plumbs the depths of greed? Is a sheep-shearer plying her shears an artist if she\u8217\'92s sufficiently clever about it? What about a farmer, is there room in his craft for art? Give a young man a shovel, a field of dirt, friends to impress, time to think, and what does he do? The priest leaves the derivation of the answer as an exercise to the audience. For the prude, the answer is a penis\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the average Jandri boy will find it funny to dig a big old ugly in the dirt. He laughs because it doubles as a drainage ditch.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Is this art?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 No.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 To place such degeneracy in the same category as the cloud of colored windows which open up the ceiling of the Gambagall\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85Well! That is an affront to the sacred.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Two days ago, Vigram heard a variation of this sermon. He didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t normally go into the temple, because that meant he\u8217\'92d have to listen to someone else speak, but he\u8217\'92d gone, and so young Mandrameen was forced to deal with the consequences. Burly old Vigram, with his gleaming scalp and long belly-beard, oiled and trimmed, smacked his rich breakfast table with a fat hand.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The Solitants are right!\u8221\'94 he roared. \u8220\'93If everyone is an artist, then the word is as useful as an unmarked weight!\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram clutched his jaw and winced. The food on his table did not accommodate his toothache. This was his leech farm, after all, so every dish\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s principal ingredient was some variation of the Meskalimi leech. This particular leech was a prized delicacy throughout the Hrkan world as its essence was said to cure infertility, and somehow, fertility as well. The meat was also quite sweet. It was also uncomfortably chewy. Every bite forced Vigram\u8217\'92s tongue into acrobatics, risking a slip. Two bites in, and the pain had him talking out the side of his cheek in an odd drawl. It hurt to hear him speak, in more ways than one.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why not choose a different word?\u8221\'94 Mandrameen suggested. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Because words must have walls,\u8221\'94 Vigram said as he pushed his plate away. \u8220\'93The true artist, I say this, the true artist is a divine instrument. They must be kept apart from the self-skinny horde.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri chowed down on the cold, crumbled chunks of what he supposed was black-sauced leech. It was quite bitter on account of the overpowering sauce, but actively trying to suppress a gag helped keep him from speaking his mind.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You know,\u8221\'94 Vigram said, \u8220\'93the Old Jandri word for \u8216\'91artist\u8217\'92 is lost to time, but there is a word in what\u8217\'92s left of that language fit for the task\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Burshegee. It means something like \u8216\'91fertile ground\u8217\'92, but in the Solitant tradition it means \u8216\'91true artist\u8217\'92.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Interesting,\u8221\'94 Mandri lied.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh, I\u8217\'92ll tell you what\u8217\'92s interesting. The old witch who gave that sermon, she said that art has nothing to do with what a person makes. Have you ever heard that? I didn\u8217\'92t understand it at first, but you know, it\u8217\'92s true. True artistry, consider this, true artistry is a state of mind. Some of the greatest artists never made anything at all.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri stuffed his mouth with a breadroll in a vain attempt to stifle himself. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I was under the impression,\u8221\'94 he said as he worked the roll into his cheek, \u8220\'93that an artist makes art.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram frowned and tutted. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Nobody makes anything,\u8221\'94 he insisted. \u8220\'93We can only ever rearrange. When you paint, you push pigment around. How is that any different than my footprints rearranging dirt? No, either everyone is an artist, or, and this is my claim, an artist is a certain kind}{\f1\fs24\b0\i1  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 of}{\f1\fs24\b0\i1  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 person. A certain kind of }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 mind}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . You know, too many big ideas, too many shallow excuses, that sort of thing. It\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s a mind marked by excess\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 not abundance\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 excess}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 .\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Don\u8217\'92t look at me.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram smiled. The easy swerve of his chubby lip looked like a baited hook snagging his tawny beard. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So exaggerated is the artist\u8217\'92s sense of self that it becomes impossible to describe them without resorting to sarcasm.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You are still looking at me.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93There\u8217\'92s no one else here.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Two slaves stood at attention by the kitchen\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s double-swing doors. Vigram\u8217\'92s blindness to their existence was cruel, but this did not dismantle his point, as Mandri did think }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 very}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  highly of himself.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Why shouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t he?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 When he was ten, he could paint a portrait in oils that rivaled the old Jeketian masters. These weren\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t polish-jobs where the paint was thin and every hair was rendered into being like he\u8217\'92d lost the plot of reality. In his hands, a single stroke of thick umber on slim black was enough to define the chestnut skin, the high-arched cheek, the skull underneath, the light, the shadow, even the mood of the piece. One single stroke! With twenty-four, he could find a vivid likeness. There might be a few extra nibbles here and there to make a beauty\u8217\'92s eyes glisten and her cleavage heave, but nobody counted those. Well, Vigram counted them. Lascivious men counted them. Every man counted them. Some women, presumably.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 And like any prideful artist, Mandri would strut around the grand Hrkan galleries and make clear his contempt for his contemporaries. He\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d stand in front of a painting and say, \u8220\'93This piece really moves me,\u8221\'94 and he\u8217\'92d make a show of walking away. All must bear witness to his mop of black hair as it flounced itself in time with his skinny, stiff-backed step. Or he\u8217\'92d say, \u8220\'93I weep at every stroke,\u8221\'94 and he\u8217\'92d flash a knowing smile. Back in those days, he\u8217\'92d say these things directly to a fellow painter\u8217\'92s face if he could get to it. He never thought of it as bullying because artists, like himself, were safe targets for playful derision; it wasn\u8217\'92t the person he was making fun of, it was their failed attempts to express themselves, and those were completely different things. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d never go after the person.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 No, never.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Artists were the best people.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It takes the best kind of person to put themselves in front of others and push through the barbs. Tough skin. Unearned confidence. A flair for the dramatic. Without any of that, an artist is doomed to obscurity. And then there\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s the servility. Above all, an artist must be servile to the hand that feeds. And look at that, Vigram had a lot of food at his table.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Vigram,\u8221\'94 Mandri said firmly, \u8220\'93you are an idiot.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram choked on a wad of smushed up, and now regurgitated, leech. He coughed, pounded his chest, then coughed again. Once recovered, he glared at Mandri with bulging eyes, oblivious to the brown specks of food caught in his beard. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93In whose house do we sit?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yours, of course,\u8221\'94 Mandri said with a disarming smile. \u8220\'93But when it comes to these things, when it comes to matters of art, I am correct. If I am not correct, then you certainly aren\u8217\'92t either.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why? Because I like some painters who aren\u8217\'92t you?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t paint anymore, so I don\u8217\'92t care who you like.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If you\u8217\'92re not a painter, then why do I pay you for lessons?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93These lessons are a charity.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mandri, I }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 pay}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  you!\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Even so.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s frown was accented by a little drip of juice coming down the corner of his lip. He wiped it away, then broke into a jolly smile. \u8220\'93Hah!\u8221\'94 he exclaimed, and he stabbed his clam shell into a bowl of fermented leech that had been mashed into so much lard that the gray paste could have greased a wheel. His outstretched tongue batted at the stringy slop before he slumped it all down his gullet. He patted his fat lips dry with his fifth napkin, then threw it onto the floor to join the others.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We both know,\u8221\'94 he said, \u8220\'93that you only come here for the money.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then we are both mistaken.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram set the soup of leech lard aside and put on his business face. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Listen,\u8221\'94 he said. \u8220\'93You have a gift. You should be rich. Painting is a sacred and lucrative discipline. I believe in your talent. You should believe me when I say that success is there for the taking. Now, I know you don\u8217\'92t want to debase yourself by doing what it takes to succeed, but there is hardly any debasement necessary. Listen to me\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the money is easy. It\u8217\'92s }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 sitting}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  there for the taking.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri settled into his chair because he knew what was coming next: Vigram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s life story. It always came out as a sort of instructional. The first step in the process was often left out because not everyone could easily inherit a sizable sum. That being said, four ounces of silver would do.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Next, loan those four ounces to a leech farm. Why a leech farm? The symbolism. But it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s important to remember that not every leech farm is the same. Look for the farms that supply Solitant temples with leeches for their bloodletting rituals. That\u8217\'92s a surefire bet because temples are always the last thing the mob will torch in lean times. When the lean times do come, and they always do, do not budge on the leech farm\u8217\'92s interest rate so as to take over the farm. The leechmen might accuse you of committing usury against Solraheen Himself, because in a way you are, but Solraheen is dead and so what does it matter? Get together with a priest and pray about it around a jug of beer, flash him a slip of silver, and the bleary shine will blind him to the iniquity.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 With the farm in hand, begin to lend smaller amounts over shorter terms to farmers who need emergency loans to pay their taxes after droughts or infestations. Split these debts up and sell them off in Meskalim\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s bond market. There\u8217\'92s not much money in Meskalim itself, but it has a busy port and that means access to all the important markets of the Hrkan world.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 From there, it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s a simple matter of reducing your eyes to fuzzy pinpricks, ridding yourself of limbs, segmenting the body, and now that you\u8217\'92ve become a leech, you can attach firmly the to the continent\u8217\'92s belly and drink your fill. Fools who try to shake you off before you\u8217\'92ve finished become your slaves. You pick out the salvageable ones for your own use, and now you\u8217\'92ve got a brood of leeches pouring over lists of sums credited and debts owed. So long as you maintain a layer of abstraction between these creatures and your debt collectors, it\u8217\'92s all self-sustaining.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 That\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Now you have a comfortable life.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Idle hours.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No debasement necessary,\u8221\'94 Vigram added before licking his}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  plump fingers clean of lechi oil. This oil was a true delicacy, squeezed as it was from the salivary glands of old leeches aged twenty years or more.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Now,\u8221\'94 Vigram said. \u8220\'93}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 You know all about the making of a painting. That\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s why I respect you. I know all about the making of money. At a certain point you have to join them up, because the world doesn\u8217\'92t work how it should. The world works how it works. You }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 have}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  to make a living. Success, Mandri, is a very sweet thing.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri wolfed down the flattened body of a sun-roasted leech, which was }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 very}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  sweet, then meekly agreed. In between chews he considered telling Vigram what he really thought, but he remembered that he sorely needed Vigram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s money.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram clapped his meaty hands and one of the nameless slaves came and took their plates. Once done, he stood up. He was a big man, so his chair protested with a litany of squeaks. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri felt small in comparison. He was small, but he didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t often feel it this intensely. When Vigram grabbed him by the shoulder and guided him out to the vine-trellised, brown-brick patio he felt like a child being led outside to play. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Then he saw the leech lakes and he shriveled up even more.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The patio overlooked twelve massive man-made leech lakes, each a perfect square. The rim of each square was lined with roofless stalls, each penning a live animal into the shallows. Goats, horses, cows; any animal larger than a big dog would do. They were each of them slumped onto support beams, and drooling, high on intoxicants. This was not an act of beneficence to inure them to the pain, it was Vigram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s way of keeping his peaceful country air free from their wild moaning.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram set himself to work in setting up an easel which he claimed to have built himself. Slaves cut and planed the lumber, brewed the glue, hammered the metal fittings, but Vigram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s mighty mind designed it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Are you sure you want to do this here?\u8221\'94 Mandri asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why not here?\u8221\'94 said Vigram.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri eyed the drooling animals in the lakes below. Each of them were shaved down to the pink skin like criminals. Leechmen waded in the waters around them, snatching the largest leeches before tossing them into grass baskets. Those leeches which weren\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t engaged in the constant struggle for the cleanest spot of flesh were busy rippling the water\u8217\'92s surface with their mating. Each lake was a sort of leech paradise. If only those foul creatures knew that they, too, were going to be eaten. Mandri had eaten some of them himself. Along with that thought came a pang of guilt, because all those animals out there were suffering just to fill his stomach.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Yes, those lakes were hard to look at.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well,\u8221\'94 Mandri said as he looked up at the patio\u8217\'92s trellis, not yet thick enough with vines. \u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s that this light is going to make things difficult. A dappled light will fall upon the sitter.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He moved into the dappled shade to demonstrate the effect on his own skin.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93My dear Mandriiii,\u8221\'94 Vigram said, his pained drawl rolling heavily. \u8220\'93The patterns of light and shadow are a magical vesture.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well,\u8221\'94 Mandri pondered, \u8220\'93I might suggest that you worry about \u8216\'91magical vestures\u8217\'92 when you\u8217\'92re skilled enough to make a face look like a face.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No,\u8221\'94 Vigram said firmly, brown beard wiggling. \u8220\'93I won\u8217\'92t have it any other way. A magical vesture for a magical subject.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 As if bidden from the heavens by Vigram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s words, his daughter, Pelora, nominally Lora, joined them on the patio. She was Vigram\u8217\'92s favorite subject, and the only child willing to sit for him. She was unmarried. Mandri\u8217\'92s age. Hardly anyone knew of her existence because Vigram kept her squirreled away. This all might lead one to assume that Vigram was an overprotective father, but no, the man was eager to see Mandri glance at his daughter\u8217\'92s figure.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Isn\u8217\'92t she a subject fit for holy oils?\u8221\'94 Vigram asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Undoubtedly,\u8221\'94 Mandri said as his eyes flicked again to Lora, without intention. Vigram interpreted this as the most rabid of intentions, and the big man was sure to make his encouragement plain by squeezing out a suggestive smile.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Lora was good natured, comely, with clear brown skin, sun-kissed cheeks, and a waist wide enough to belong to a fertility goddess. Many a man would leap at the chance, but Mandri had no desire to sire children. He averted his gaze, but that was a mistake because there were was no where else to look except for those leech lakes. One of the nearest torture victims, an old yellow ox, arrested Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s wandering eye. It seemed ask him for help. It mooed, bucked against its restraints, then mooed again.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93White light!\u8221\'94 Vigram roared as he rushed to the edge of the patio. \u8220\'93Quiet that animal!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The leechmen below scurried into action.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93And you,\u8221\'94 Vigram said to Mandri, \u8220\'93help her up. I\u8217\'92ll ready the canvas and paint.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri sighed a sigh for the old ox, and privately resolved to never eat a leech again. It was the least he could do. Well, it was the most he could do. Then he did what he was told helped Lora up onto a high-legged stool. Lora let her fingers linger on his arm as he pulled away.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Stop distracting my muse,\u8221\'94 Vigram teased.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Again, Mandri did as he was told and took up his post behind the old man.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram snatched up a stick of soft charcoal and put down his first exploratory marks. This was always the most difficult phase. Every work of art must be built on a firm foundation; get it wrong and everything that comes after will be wrong as well. Unfortunately for Vigram, he had that all too common beginner\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s habit of refusing to use his god damned brain. He started drawing wherever his hand happened to land, and whatever happened next was up to Solraheen. The end result was that Lora\u8217\'92s head was half the size it needed to be. It was also too left-of-center. There\u8217\'92d be an awkward expanse behind her flower-studded curls.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Hold on,\u8221\'94 said Mandri. \u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re moving too fast. Don\u8217\'92t think of this as a portrait\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 not yet. All we have right now is an oval, a rectangular canvas, and where that oval sits on that canvas. All you\u8217\'92re doing is putting an oval on a rectangle.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Right.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So, think about, where\u8217\'92s the best place to put that oval? How big should it be? Remember, you have the whole canvas there.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes. Yes, you\u8217\'92re right.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram rubbed the marks away with his palm.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He stepped back.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He studied Lora.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He stepped again to the canvas, then scratched another black oval exactly where the first had been.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Is that better?\u8221\'94 he asked with all the awareness of a potted plant. \u8220\'93Do you think it needs to be bigger?\u8221\'94 He then drew the oval again, but only slightly larger. From then on, every other mark he made was accompanied by a look back to Mandri for reassurance. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Don\u8217\'92t look at me,\u8221\'94 said Mandri, frustrated. \u8220\'93Look at her.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93But I need to know if the marks I make are correct.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93They\u8217\'92re never correct.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 There was a glimmer of understanding in Vigram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eye, but just as soon as it came it faded. \u8220\'93If the mark I make is always wrong, then how could I ever move past it? I\u8217\'92ll be redrawing the same line over and over again.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You move on when you can\u8217\'92t stand to try anymore.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That sounds miserable.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It is. You should feel defeated by the time you\u8217\'92re finished. In fact, you should never feel good about what you\u8217\'92re doing, because that means you\u8217\'92re not trying hard enough. Now, finish\u8230\'85finish the basic shapes, at least.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Alright.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91finished\u8217\'92 the \u8216\'91basic shapes\u8217\'92. He looked to Mandri for final approval.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s your paint,\u8221\'94 Mandri said with a shrug. \u8220\'93But you need to understand the importance of the drawing. Draw and redraw. Painting is drawing.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I understand. You talk about it all the time.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Damn it!\u8221\'94 He cried.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Oh, please,\u8221\'94 Lora sighed. \u8220\'93Let the men work.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That is precisely the problem; they\u8217\'92re }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 not}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  working. If they were, I wouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t have heard that noise!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram tossed his charcoal over his shoulder and squealed with delight as he picked up his favorite brush. He dipped into a random paint, then threw down the first splotches of color in a flurry. The man was building an affront to the senses, and like a notary to an execution, Mandri was getting paid to witness it. And Sol\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s light, that stretched sheet of bentberrry canvas was innocent. It was an expensive fiber, too, coveted for its depth of feeling, for how it made the undertones blush. Here, they were bruised and near to bleeding.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri glanced in Lora\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s direction. He had to. Of course, the moment his eyes wandered over her exposed shoulder, her smile perked up. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mandri, stop flirting with my daughter.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram gave Mandri another encouraging smile.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I am not flirting,\u8221\'94 Mandri claimed. \u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m checking proportions.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes, and how }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 are}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  her proportions?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The old goat\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyebrows jumped suggestively. Lora, for her part, squirmed in her seat, blushing in feigned embarrassment, absolutely loving it.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s it! That\u8217\'92s IT!\u8221\'94 He rushed again to the edge of the patio. Down below, the yellow ox had somehow gotten loose. It was , waking kickup a wake of confused copulated leeches. \u8220\'93Look at it! There must be a silver-string worth of leeches attached to that ox!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Please,\u8221\'94 Lora said from her seat, \u8220\'93We hardly need the money from another bundle of leeches. There are more important things. Let it go.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You are asking me to let go of my principles. That I cannot do.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Vigram,\u8221\'94 Lora said, her tone darkening. \u8220\'93Let it go.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram cowed. What kind of daughter orders her father around by his first name? And Vigram. He retreated from the scene the leechmen wading after the splashing ox and returned to the canvas. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93This depresses me,\u8221\'94 he said as he watched his charcoal guidlines bleed what looked like pus. \u8220\'93You know what? I need a break. You two\u8230\'85why don\u8217\'92t you two clean up?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram set his brush down rather quickly, and he wiped his charcoal-stained fingers on an untouched corner of the canvas.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Where are you going?\u8221\'94 Mandri asked as the old man plodded off.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m going to pick out some wine. I need to clear my mind. Something with a sweet bouquet always relaxes me.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93But you aren\u8217\'92t finished.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I know. I\u8217\'92ll be back. You two\u8230\'85you two get along.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram exchanged an excited look with Lora. one of the house\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s misty window panes, behind which Vigram\u8217\'92s bearded face was smiling wide, as if about to stamp a return on interest.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Lora slid off her stool.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 She sauntered over to Mandri and her intrepid hand brushed the back of his arm. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Let me see what my father has\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 OH my GOD!\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 She recoiled in horror at the sight of her melted visage dripping down the oversized canvas. She squeezed Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s scrawny shoulders as she hid herself behind him, pressing herself against him in genuine fright.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It could be better,\u8221\'94 Mandri said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s horrible!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I think it\u8217\'92s the hands.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri stepped forward to make a play at correcting the hands. Lora sidled forward with him, stifling a laugh as she moved.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93He\u8217\'92s turned me into a demon!\u8221\'94 she exclaimed. \u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s not only the hands\u8230\'85though they do look like claws.\u8221\'94 She grabbed Mandri\u8217\'92s own hand. She gave it a squeeze. \u8220\'93Artists need strong and dexterous hands, don\u8217\'92t they?\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Uh\u8230\'85no\u8230\'85\u8221\'94 Mandri stammered. \u8220\'93Well, yes, but, uh\u8230\'85 I don\u8217\'92t have any, uh, dexterity. I actually haven\u8217\'92t painted anything in years.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Don\u8217\'92t be ridiculous, I\u8217\'92ve seen you paint.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93These lessons don\u8217\'92t really count.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then what have you been doing up on that little farm of yours?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Farming.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Lora rolled her eyes. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Look at you,\u8221\'94 she said. \u8220\'93You\u8217\'92ve never farmed a day in your life.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Are you calling me a liar?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well why don\u8217\'92t you paint anymore?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That would be difficult to explain,\u8221\'94 Mandri said as he tore himself away from her grip. He tried to busy himself with Vigram\u8217\'92s mess, as there was enough untouched pigment left on the palette for at least four more of these awkward lessons. He moved to scrape a slap of yellow back into its little clay jar.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Try to explain it,\u8221\'94 said Lora.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, painting is, uh...\u8221\'94 Mandri struggled to think of a palatable excuse, but that was difficult because his legs were sweating. His body was readying him for flight. \u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s too expensive,\u8221\'94 he said instinctively. \u8220\'93Look at all this pigment. The canvas. It would take me weeks to afford all this. Your father makes this in half a finger.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You could make that much too if you came and worked for him.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t want to do that.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Lora picked up a dirty brush and twirled its horse-hair head through the muddy colors of the palette. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You know, he doesn\u8217\'92t actually care about learning to paint. The only reason he pays for these lessons is because you would starve if he didn\u8217\'92t. He likes you. I like you.\u8221\'94 She batted her eyes and tried to catch him staring.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t need charity.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Mandri, I\u8217\'92ve seen your farm. My dad\u8217\'92s seen your farm. Everyone\u8217\'92s seen your farm. It\u8217\'92s not a farm.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It is to me.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Lora rolled the handle of the paintbrush in between her fingers; a suggestive stroke. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The girls in Meskalim all say that you\u8217\'92re a eunuch.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93They say that you\u8217\'92re a eunuch.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m not a eunuch.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Prove it,\u8221\'94 she said as she moved dangerously close. This was kissing distance. This close, sly, expectant look was sure to rouse. \u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m a woman, Mandri. What\u8217\'92s your problem?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m not going to pull my uglies out just to prove they\u8217\'92re there.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Lora grabbed his arm and pulled him closer. She caught his eyes, forced him to confront her lilac scent, her pounding heat, her smooth skin, her honeyed, aching lips.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Lora\u8230\'85\u8221\'94 Mandri muttered. He knew he had to be very careful here. \u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re a beautiful girl, but\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93But what? You go in for men?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I could be good for you.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93And what do you get out of it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 She squeezed herself against him. Her warmth was overwhelming.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You could be good for me,\u8221\'94 she said. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You would not say that if you knew me.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What\u8217\'92s there to know? You\u8217\'92re just a boy.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eyes widened at the sight of her inviting smile. The soft shadows of the vines overhead just so happened to frame her hazel eyes with the most magnificent golden light\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a magical vesture indeed. He probably would have given in if his gaze hadn\u8217\'92t stumbled over the sight of a giant yellow ox hurtling towards them both. It\u8217\'92s haunches were covered in swinging leeches.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri pushed Lora out of the way. He dived aside himself. The old ox, sagging spine and all, rammed right through the thin trellis wood then stumbled on the patio brick. It crashed into Vigram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s easel, launching at least a dozen leeches into the air as it did.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93MRRRRUUUUUU!\u8221\'94 the ox bleated as its hooves scratched and slipped on the patio brick. When it regained its feet, it burst out of the opposite side of the patio trellis, then went scampering down.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s heart was in his chest.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s interesting,\u8221\'94 Lora said, almost amused. \u8220\'93I did not see that coming.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93This is not what I\u8217\'92m here for,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. He got up to his feet and took off running.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What is wrong with you?!\u8221\'94 Lora shouted after him.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri did not answer. There was no point in answering. This was not what he was here for.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 What }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 was}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  he here for?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He stopped, turned, and behold, there was big Vigram, marching fast with his robe hiked up and long beard tucked under his armpit.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What happened!?\u8221\'94 Vigram shouted.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri got to his feet. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m leaving,\u8221\'94 he said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re leaving? But what happened.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The ox,\u8221\'94 Lora said }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri waited for Vigram to catch up. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Look,\u8221\'94 he said, \u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t want to be a bother, but could I get the money I\u8217\'92m owed?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram reached into his robe and pulled out a small brown sack of coin. He held it in the air as if to lure Mandri back towards the house.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Let him go,\u8221\'94 Lora said. \u8220\'93This wasn\u8217\'92t meant to be.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It wasn\u8217\'92t?\u8221\'94 Ayram asked, seemingly hurt. \u8220\'93We could still\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93An ox interrupted,\u8221\'94 Lora said coldly. \u8220\'93What are the chances? This was not meant to be.\u8221\'94 Seemingly suggesting somethign mysterious. \u8220\'93Pay him his money.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You want me to pay him?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram reluctance.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Are you going to stiff me?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I was going to do something different entirely. But, things as they are, here you are.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Drops the coin into mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s hand.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Until we meet again,\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 When he got to the top of the big hill that overlooked Vigram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s estate, he took one last look back.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The ox was nowhere to be seen.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Vigram was Marshalling a posse of his leechmen to go hunt it down.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The old man saw Mandri, then cupped his voice and shouted, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No burgeons!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yeah, yeah,\u8221\'94 Mandri muttered under his breath.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93They\u8217\'92ll douse your Spark!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri waved again, then walked all the way to Geem\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s. There he bought half a bushel of burgeons. They were down-valley burgeons, decent stuff, but the waxy capsule leaves were a bit too brittle, so they\u8217\'92d split too quick. The insides would dry out before he could get to them in the ways that he wanted to. But that was all Geem had, so he bought them.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri continued along the road, stomping his way through the muddy wheel-ruts, slapping away the flies, humming nursery rhymes until he made it back to his farm. There he could finally relax and lose all sense of himself in the deep and blessed bliss brought on by a milky hooch spiked through with burgeon juice.}}